{"slug": "crucible", "root": "crucible", "category": "alchemy", "gloss": "a melting-vessel", "definition": "A *crucible* is a small, thick-walled vessel of clay or fired ceramic built to hold metals and minerals over a fierce open fire until they fuse. Unlike a *retort* or *alembic*, which carry off vapors, the crucible keeps its charge in place to melt, mix, and purify. It is the shared workbench of assayers, smelters, and alchemists.", "history": "Medieval Latin *crucibulum* meant a melting-pot — and also a night-lamp — and medieval scribes, hearing *crux*, 'cross,' half-linked the little pot to an ordeal of fire. The turn is the metaphor that outlived the apparatus. Renaissance readers of Dee and Ashmole cast the alchemist himself as a kind of crucible wherein the soul is purified along with the object of his external operations; Pico threw all doctrines into the crucible of his thought. From that image comes our sense of a crucible as any severe test that refines what passes through it — the vessel's fire lent to trials of the spirit.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Brann, on the Fasciculus chemicus (Arthur Dee / Ashmole / Abraham)", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Attrell & Porreca, Picatrix: A Medieval Treatise on Astral Magic", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Etymonline, s.v. crucible", "where": "Etymology reference"}], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"lang": "Latin", "origin": "Medieval Latin crucibulum 'melting-pot, night-lamp'", "first": "late 14c.", "note": "An ordeal is a 'crucible' by metaphor from the alchemist's fierce little pot; medieval scribes linked it to crux, 'cross'.", "hook": "Why a hard test is a 'crucible'."}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 4, "oracle_total": 0, "in_flavor_cards": 3, "in_oracle_cards": 0, "na